messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path
- /api/users
- There are no path parameters for this endpoint (no {id} etc. in this route).

HTTP methods and acceptability (based on the code)

- All HTTP methods acceptable: No
  - The route defines only POST (registerUser) and GET (getUsers). Other methods are not defined on this path.

- HEAD: Yes
  - There is a GET handler for this path, and Express handles HEAD requests for GET routes by default (no explicit HEAD handler needed). This is based on how Express behaves with GET routes.

- POST: Yes
  - Defined on the path as router.route('/').post(registerUser).

- OPTIONS: No
  - There is no explicit OPTIONS handler for this path in the code.

- TRACE: No
  - Not defined in the code for this path.

- GET: Yes
  - Defined as router.route('/').get(protect, admin, getUsers).

- PUT: No
  - Not defined for this path.

- DELETE: No
  - Not defined for this path.

- PATCH: No
  - Not defined for this path.

Explanation
- The server mounts userRoutes at /api/users in server.js. In routes/userRoutes.js, the route for '/' (which becomes /api/users) defines POST (registerUser) and GET (getUsers) only. There are no explicit handlers for HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PUT, DELETE, or PATCH on this path, though HEAD is effectively supported by Express due to the GET handler. The presence of POST and GET confirms the allowed methods on /api/users are POST and GET, with GET further protected by auth middleware (protect, admin). All other HTTP methods are not handled on this endpoint by the provided code.
